  <title>Geometrical constructions</title>
      <subsection xml:id="subsec-Measuring-angles">
        <title>Measuring angles</title>
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Work in pairs
                </p>

                <p>
                    What you need:A protractor and a ruler.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Explore
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                (a) Individually, draw different types of angles.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                (b) Measure the angles using a protractor.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                compare the angles you have drawn with those of your friend.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Discuss how you would measure the angle shown below.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <image>
                    <latex-image width="20">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \usetikzlibrary{quotes,angles}
                        \draw(-3,1)coordinate(A)--(0,0)coordinate(B)--(-3,-1)coordinate(C); 
                        <!-- \node at (-3.1,1.2){A};
                        \node at (0.2,0){B};
                        \node at (-3.1,-1.2){C};  -->
                        \pic[draw,-&gt;,black, angle radius=0.5cm] {angle=C--B--A};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>    
                </image>
                <p>
                    Connect
                </p>

                <p>
                    Angles can be of different types depending on their sizes.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Bisecting-angles">
        <title>Bisecting angles</title>
            <activity>
                <p>
                    What you need: A ruler, a pair of compasses and a protractor.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Explore
                </p>
                <sidebyside>
                    <p>
                                1.Draw angle ABC of any size. With point B as the centre and
                                using a suitable radius, make arcs on line AB and BC as shown
                                on the right. Label the points where the arcs meet lines AB and BC
                                as M and N respectively.
                    </p>
                    
                    <image source="//a1.png" width="40%">
                        <shortdescription>explanetion</shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </sidebyside>
                <sidebyside>
                    <p>
                        2.Using the same radius and with the points M and N as the centres, make arcs inside angle ABC to meet at point P as shown on the right.
                    </p>
                    <image source="/a2.png" width="50%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </sidebyside>

                <sidebyside>
                    <p>
                    3.Using a ruler, join B  to P as shown below.
                </p>
                </sidebyside>
                <image source="/a3.png" width="40%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                </image>

                <p>
                    4.Measure angle ABP and PBC. What do you notice?
                </p>

                <p>
                    Connect.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The line that bisects an angle is called an angle bisector.
                </p>
            </activity>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                Exercise. 
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Constucting-angle-90">
        <title>Constucting <m>90^\circ</m></title>
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Work in pairs.
                </p>

                <p>
                    What you need: A ruler, a protractor and a pair of compasses.
                </p>

                <p>
                    1.Draw a straight line and mark on it point <m>O</m>. With point <m>O</m> as the centre, make arcs to cut the line at <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> as shown below.
                </p>
                    <image source="/l1.png" width="40%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>

                <p>
                   2. Using <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> as the centres, make arcs abave the line to meet at point <m>C</m> as shown below.
                </p>

                    <image source="/l2.png" width="40%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>

                <p>
                  3.Join points <m>O</m> to <m>C</m> as shown below.measure angle <m>BOC</m> and <m>COA</m>. Which angles have you constructed?  
                </p>

                    <image source="/l3.png" width="40%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>

                <p>
                    Expected observations
                </p>

                <p>
                    <me>\angle BOC = \angle COA = 90^\circ</me>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Constructing-angle-60">
        <title>Constructing <m>60^\circ</m></title>
            <activity>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Work in pairs
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        What you need: A ruler, a protractor and a pair of compasses.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Explore
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        1.Draw a straight line and mark a point <m>O</m> on it as shown below.
                    </p>

                    <image source="/l4.png" width="40%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>

                    <p>
                    2. With <m>O</m> as center draw an arc of any radius to cut the line at <m>A</m>.With the same radius and <m>A</m> as center draw an arc to cut the previous arc at <m>B</m>.
